{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586693"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15091"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64457"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7779"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49889"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21250"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64457"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral substances in urine can either promote or inhibit the formation of kidney stones (renal tract calculi). Stone inhibitors help prevent crystal formation and aggregation in the urinary tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances acts as a natural inhibitor of kidney stone formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium","Cysteine","Magnesium","Oxalate","Phosphate urate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStone inhibitors are substances that prevent or slow the formation of kidney stones. \u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium\u003C/strong\u003E is a natural inhibitor that works by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBinding to oxalate, reducing its availability for calcium oxalate stone formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInterfering with crystal growth and aggregation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreasing the solubility of calcium oxalate\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxalate\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ephosphate urate\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecysteine\u003C/strong\u003E are common constituents of kidney stones:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECalcium oxalate stones (most common)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUric acid stones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EStruvite stones (magnesium ammonium phosphate)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECystine stones (less common)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Magnesium is a natural inhibitor of kidney stone formation by binding to oxalate and reducing crystal formation","Calcium, oxalate, urate, and cysteine are common components of kidney stones rather than inhibitors"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences. \t\tFontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49889"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49889"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T17:24:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T17:24:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7779"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64457"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13